Question Text:
Examine the following show command output on a router configured for dynamic NAT:
"— Inside Source
access-list 1 pool examsdigest
pool examsdigest: netmask 255.255.255.240
start 190.1.1.1 end 190.1.1.10
type generic, total addresses 10, allocated 10 (100%), misses 595"
You are responsible to find out why users are not being able to reach the Internet.
Choices:
a. The cause is not related to dynamic NAT
b. The command output does not provide any clue to identify the problem
c. Dynamic NAT can't use Standard ACLs
d. The NAT pool does not have enough entries to fulfill the user's requests
LLM Explanation: The output shows that the NAT pool 'examsdigest' has a total of 10 addresses, all of which have been allocated. The 'misses' counter indicates there have been 595 requests that could not be fulfilled due to lack of available addresses in the pool. This suggests the NAT pool is undersized and does not have enough entries to handle the number of users/requests, preventing some users from accessing the Internet.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 10: Network Address Translation', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/network-address-translation-nat/13772-12.html']

Question Text: R1 and R2 are attached to the same Ethernet VLAN, with subnet 192.168.1.0/24, and addresses 192.168.1.1, 192.168.2 respectively. The routers use an FHRP. Host A and host B attach to the same LAN and have correct default router settings per the FHRP configuration. Which of the following statements is true for this LAN?
Choices:
a. You can't connect two routers to the same LAN subnet.
b. If one router fails, hosts can't send packets off-subnet
c. If one router fails, both hosts will use the one remaining router as a default router
d. if one router fails, only one of the two hosts will still be able to send packets off-subnet
LLM Explanation: In a LAN with two routers using a First Hop Redundancy Protocol (FHRP) like HSRP or VRRP, if one router fails, the other router will take over as the active router. All hosts on the LAN will then use the remaining active router as their default gateway to send packets off-subnet. The FHRP ensures that there is always an active router available to forward traffic, providing redundancy and preventing a single point of failure.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Chapter 16: First Hop Redundancy Protocol', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/hot-standby-router-protocol-hsrp/9234-hsrpguidetoc.html']

Question Text: What information can you extract having the IP address 172.16.99.45? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. The network ID is 172.0.0.0.
b. The default mask for the network is 255.255.255.0.
c. The network is a Class B network.
d. The number of host bits in the unsubnetted network is 16.
e. The broadcast address of the network is 172.255.255.255

Question Text:
The senior network engineer asked you to choose the last usable address for a host from the last subnet according to the following details:
Network 9.0.0.0 (Class A)
Mask 255.255.0.0 (for all subnets)
LLM Explanation: The network 9.0.0.0 with mask 255.255.0.0 is a Class A network divided into 256 subnets, each with 65,534 usable host addresses. The last subnet in this network would be 9.255.0.0/16. The last usable host address in this subnet is obtained by setting all host bits to 1 except the last bit, which is set to 0. This results in the IP address 9.255.255.254, which is the last usable host address in the last subnet of the given network.

Question Text: A Layer 2 switch configuration places all its physical ports into VLAN 2. The IP addressing plan shows that address 175.28.1.150 (with mask 255.255.255.0) is reserved for use by this new LAN switch and that 175.28.1.254 is already configured on the router connected to that same VLAN. The switch needs to support SSH connections into the switch from any subnet in the network. Which of the following commands are part of the required configuration in this case? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. The switch cannot support SSH because all its ports connect to VLAN 2, and the IP address must be configured on interface VLAN 1.
b. The ip address 175.28.1.150 255.255.255.0 command in interface vlan 2 configuration mode.
c. The ip default-gateway 175.28.1.254 command in global configuration mode.
d. The ip address 172.16.2.250 255.255.255.0 command in interface vlan 1 configuration mode.
e. The ip default-gateway 175.28.1.150 command in global configuration mode.
LLM Explanation: To configure the Layer 2 switch with the given IP address and enable SSH access, the switch needs an IP address on the VLAN interface corresponding to the VLAN where all ports are assigned (VLAN 2 in this case). This is done with the 'ip address 175.28.1.150 255.255.255.0' command in interface vlan 2 configuration mode. Additionally, the switch needs a default gateway configured to reach other subnets, which is set with the 'ip default-gateway 175.28.1.254' command in global configuration mode, using the router's IP address in that VLAN.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 8: Configuring Basic Switch Management', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/switches/lan/catalyst2960/software/release/15-2_2_e/configuration/guide/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg/b_1522e_2960_2960c_2960s_2960sf_2960p_cg_chapter_01001.html']

Question Text: Which of the following have examples of parallel composition? Select all that apply.
Choices:
a. Perform load balancing on any traffic that arrives from prefix 130.207.0.0/16 or is destined to port 80.
b. Perform MAC learning on all traffic that is not blocked by a firewall rule.
c. Count all port 80 traffic.
d. Block all traffic whose source IP address is contained in a list of blocked IP addresses.
e. Load balance traffic across multiple destination IP addresses and perform routing to the resulting destination IP addresses.
LLM Explanation: Parallel composition involves applying multiple policies or actions to the same traffic simultaneously. In choice (a), load balancing is performed on traffic that matches either of two conditions (source prefix or destination port), which is an example of parallel composition. Similarly, choice (e) applies both load balancing and routing policies to the same traffic, another case of parallel composition. The other choices describe sequential or conditional compositions rather than parallel.
URLs: ['https://opennetworking.org/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/openflow-spec-v1.3.0.pdf', 'https://www.sdxcentral.com/networking/sdn/definitions/what-is-openflow/', 'https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/computer-science/parallel-composition']

Question Text: Which of the following is the appropriate Pyretic rule for matching traffic that sends packets from either 10.0.0.1 or 10.0.0.2 to IP address 1.2.3.4?
Choices:
a. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) + mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
b. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) + mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
c. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
d. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4))
e. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)
LLM Explanation: The correct Pyretic rule for matching traffic from either source IP 10.0.0.1 or 10.0.0.2 to destination IP 1.2.3.4 is '(match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + match(srcip=10.0.0.2)) >> mod(dstip=1.2.3.4)'. The '+' operator performs a parallel composition, matching packets from either source IP. The '>>' operator then performs a sequential composition, modifying the destination IP of the matched packets to 1.2.3.4.
URLs: ['Pyretic Language Tutorial, https://github.com/frenetic-lang/pyretic/wiki/Language-Tutorial', 'Pyretic Operator Documentation, https://github.com/frenetic-lang/pyretic/wiki/Pyretic-Operators']

Question Text: Which of the following is the appropiate Pyretic rule for sending traffic from source IP address 10.0.0.1 to destination IP address 10.1.2.3 and traffic from source IP address 10.0.0.2 to destination IP address 10.2.3.4?
Choices:
a. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2)  + mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
b. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
c. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >>mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
d. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) + mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) >> (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) + mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
e. (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) & (match(srcip=10.0.0.2)  >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4))
LLM Explanation: The correct Pyretic rule for sending traffic from source IP 10.0.0.1 to destination IP 10.1.2.3 and traffic from source IP 10.0.0.2 to destination IP 10.2.3.4 is option b: (match(srcip=10.0.0.1) >> mod(dstip=10.1.2.3)) + (match(srcip=10.0.0.2) >> mod(dstip=10.2.3.4)). The '>>' operator in Pyretic represents a sequential composition, meaning the first policy is applied followed by the second policy. The '+' operator represents parallel composition, allowing the two policies to be applied independently. Options a, c, d, and e use incorrect combinations of these operators for the desired traffic forwarding.

Question Text: Given the following IP address - 20.54.23.3 and subnet mask - 255.255.255.0 choose the subnet ID and the broadcast address from that particular IP.

Question Text:
You are working with a network engineer to design a network for the new Campus. He provided the following details:
The IP address is 195.240.37.43
The subnet mask is 255.255.255.224
You have been tasked to find the:
1. Network (N) bits
2. Subnet bits (S)
3. Host (H) bits.
Choices:
a. Network Bits = 15 | Subnet Bits = 2 | Host Bits = 1
b. Network Bits = 20 | Subnet Bits = 3 | Host Bits = 1
c. Network Bits = 24 | Subnet Bits = 3 | Host Bits = 5
d. Network Bits = 28 | Subnet Bits = 1 | Host Bits = 2
LLM Explanation: To determine the number of network, subnet, and host bits, we need to analyze the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.255.255.224 in binary is 11111111.11111111.11111111.11100000. Counting the number of consecutive 1s from the left gives us the total number of network and subnet bits combined, which is 27. The default subnet mask for a Class C IP address (first octet 192-223) is 255.255.255.0, which has 24 network bits. Therefore, the number of subnet bits is 27 - 24 = 3. The remaining bits (32 - 27 = 5) are used for host addresses.

Question Text: Your task is to find the broadcast address from the IP address 10.75.20.3 with subnet mask 255.248.0.0

a. Broadcast address: 10.75.255.255
b. Broadcast address: 10.75.20.255
c. Broadcast address: 10.79.255.255
d. Broadcast address: 10.80.255.255
LLM Explanation: To find the broadcast address, we need to identify the network and host portions of the IP address based on the subnet mask. The subnet mask 255.248.0.0 (/13) means that the first 13 bits are network bits, and the remaining 19 bits are host bits. In binary, 10.75.20.3 is 00001010.01001011.00010100.00000011. The first 13 bits (00001010.01001) represent the network portion, and the last 19 bits (011.00010100.00000011) represent the host portion. To get the broadcast address, we keep the network bits the same and set all host bits to 1. This gives us 00001010.01001111.11111111.11111111, which is 10.79.255.255 in decimal notation.

Question Text: Which of the following masks, when used within a Class B network, would supply enough subnet bits to support 90 subnets? (Choose two)
LLM Explanation: To support 90 subnets in a Class B network, we need at least 7 subnet bits (since 2^7 = 128, which is greater than 90). A /19 mask (choice c) borrows 3 bits from the host portion, providing 11 subnet bits in total, which is more than enough. The 255.255.224.0 mask (choice f) is equivalent to /19, as it has 11 network bits set to 1 in the third octet (11100000 in binary). The other masks either borrow too few bits to support 90 subnets (/24, /21, and 255.255.240.0) or are invalid for a Class B network (255.255.255.252).
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 13: Subnet Design', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Criteria #3: Permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets

Choices:
a. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.255.255.255
b. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.255.255
c. access-list 1 permit 56.58.0.0 0.0.255.255
d. access-list 1 permit 56.57.0.0 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: To permit packets from hosts with 56.57 as the first two octets, the correct wildcard mask should be 0.0.255.255. This wildcard mask matches any value in the last two octets while fixing the first two octets as 56.57. Option 'a' uses an incorrect wildcard mask that would match any value in the last three octets. Options 'c' and 'd' have incorrect wildcard masks and also do not match the 56.57 criteria in the first two octets.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #4: Permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5, sent to a web server in subnet 65.5.6.0/24
ACL command #4: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq 23
b. access-list 101 permit any any
c. access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
d. access-list 101 deny tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is c. The ACL command 'access-list 101 permit tcp host 65.5.5.5 65.5.6.0 0.0.0.255 eq www' matches the given criteria. It permits TCP traffic from the specific host 65.5.5.5 to any host in the 65.5.6.0/24 subnet, but only if the destination port is www (HTTP). This aligns with the requirement to permit packets from web client 65.5.5.5 to a web server in the specified subnet.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Configuration Guide, Release 12.4 - Configuring IP Access Lists: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios/security/configuration/guide/12_4/sec_12_4_book/sec_access_list_overview.html', 'Cisco IOS IP Command Reference, Volume 1 of 3: Addressing and Services, Release 12.2 - IP Services Commands: access-list: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios/12_2/ipaddr/command/reference/fipras_r/1rfip1.html#wp1018617']

Question Text:
Your task is to type a one-line extended ACL that matches the following criteria. All access-list commands use the number 101 in the command.
Criteria #5: Permit any and every IPv4 packet
ACL command #5: ______________________
Choices:
a. access-list 101 permit ip any any
b. access-list 101 deny ip any any
c. access-list 101 permit ip 0.0.0.0 any
d. access-list 101 permit ip any 0.0.0.0
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit any and every IPv4 packet in an extended ACL is 'access-list 101 permit ip any any'. This command uses the wildcard mask 'any' for both the source and destination IP addresses, effectively matching all IPv4 packets.

Question Text: Type the access-list command that permits all packets sent from hosts in subnet 14.15.16.0/24. Use the ACL number 50 for the ACL rule.
Choices:
a. access-list 50 permit 14.15.17.0 0.0.0.255
b. access-list 50 deny 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
c. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.255.255.255
d. access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255
LLM Explanation: The correct command to permit all packets from the 14.15.16.0/24 subnet is 'access-list 50 permit 14.15.16.0 0.0.0.255'. The ACL number 50 is used as specified. The subnet mask 0.0.0.255 is the wildcard mask equivalent of the /24 prefix, allowing any host within that subnet. The other options have incorrect wildcard masks or use 'deny' instead of 'permit'.

Question Text: Given the following access-list command access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255, choose the exact range of IP addresses, matched by the command.
LLM Explanation: The access-list command 'access-list 2 permit 192.168.4.0 0.0.0.255' matches the IP address range 192.168.4.0 - 192.168.4.255. The first part '192.168.4.0' specifies the network address, while the second part '0.0.0.255' is the wildcard mask. The wildcard mask determines which bits of the IP address can vary. In this case, only the last octet can vary from 0 to 255, resulting in the range 192.168.4.0 to 192.168.4.255.
URLs: ['Cisco CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']

Question Text:
The ACL 55 on R1 has four statements, in the following order, with address and wildcard mask values as follows:
1. 20.0.0.0 0.255.255.255
2. 20.20.0.0 0.0.255.255
3. 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255
4. 2.2.2.0 0.0.0.255
If a router tried to match a packet sourced from IP address 20.20.20.20 using this ACL, which ACL statement does a router consider the packet to have matched?
Choices:
a. First statement
b. Second statement
c. Third statement
d. Forth statement
e. Implied deny at the end of the ACL
LLM Explanation: When a router processes an ACL, it goes through the statements in sequential order from top to bottom. It stops processing and considers the packet matched at the first statement where there is a match. In this case, the IP address 20.20.20.20 would match the third statement 20.20.20.0 0.0.0.255 because the wildcard mask of 0.0.0.255 means that only the first three octets need to match exactly. The fourth octet can be anything from 0 to 255. So the router would consider this packet matched by the third ACL statement and stop processing further.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 2, by Wendell Odom, Chapter 16: Access Control Lists', 'https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/security/ios-firewall/23602-confaccesslists.html']
SM - Description: Calculates the first few options incorrectly
SM - Misunderstanding Reasons: An error related to misinterpreting IP addresses
Effect - Description of effects: Could have a major effect on ACL
Effect - Error Type: configuration issues, security issues, debugging delay

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, any source IP address with source port greater than 10455, a destination IP address 30.3.3.3 and a destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 28
b. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny tcp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp any gt 25 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is b. The access-list command 'access-list 101 deny udp any gt 10455 host 30.3.3.3 eq 25' matches the given criteria: - It denies UDP packets (not TCP as in option c) - The source IP is 'any' - The source port is greater than 10455 - The destination IP is the specific host 30.3.3.3 - The destination port equals 25 (not 28 as in option a) Option d is incorrect because it checks for source port greater than 25 instead of 10455.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Command Reference: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/security/a1/sec-a1-cr-book.html', 'Cisco IOS Access Lists Cheat Sheet: https://packetlife.net/media/library/13/Cisco_IOS_Access_Lists.pdf']

Question Text: Which of the following access-list denies packets with a UDP header, a source IP address 30.3.3.3 and a source port greater than 10455, any destination IP address 30.3.3.3 with destination port equal to 25?
Choices:
a. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 30
b. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 25 any eq 25
c. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.0.0.0 gt 10455 any eq 25
d. access-list 101 deny udp host 30.3.3.3 gt 10455 any eq 25
LLM Explanation: The correct access list to deny the specified UDP packets is 'd'. It has the correct protocol (UDP), source IP address (30.3.3.3), source port (greater than 10455), destination IP (any), and destination port (equal to 25). Option 'a' has an incorrect destination port of 30. Option 'b' has an incorrect source port of greater than 25. Option 'c' has an incorrect source IP address of 30.0.0.0.
URLs: ['Cisco IOS Security Configuration Guide, Release 12.4 - Configuring IP Access Lists: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios/security/configuration/guide/12_4/sec_12_4_book/sec_access_list_ov.html', 'Cisco IOS IP Addressing Services Command Reference - access-list: https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/td/docs/ios-xml/ios/ipaddr/command/ipaddr-cr-book/ipaddr-a1.html#wp3893541320']

Question Text: Choose the wildcard mask that matches all IP packets in the subnet 46.45.44.0, and mask 255.255.255.0.
LLM Explanation: The wildcard mask is the inverse of the subnet mask. Given the subnet mask is 255.255.255.0, the wildcard mask would be 0.0.0.255. This wildcard mask will match all IP addresses in the 46.45.44.0/24 subnet.

Question Text: You have noticed that a server with IP 145.45.3.2 doesn’t respond to requests. What command will you type first in order to test connectivity between your device and the server?
LLM Explanation: The 'ping' command is the correct choice to test connectivity between your device and the server with IP address 145.45.3.2. Ping uses ICMP echo request and echo reply messages to determine if a host is reachable and responsive on an IP network. It measures the round-trip time for messages and reports errors or packet loss, making it a simple but effective tool for troubleshooting network connectivity issues.

Question Text: After configuring a working router interface with IP address/mask 10.1.1.100/26, which of the following routes would you expect to see in the output of the show ip route command? (Choose two answers.)
Choices:
a. A connected route for subnet 10.1.1.64 255.255.255.192
b. A local route for host 10.1.1.64 255.255.255.255
c. A local route for host 10.1.1.100 255.255.255.255
d. A local route for host 10.1.1.100 255.255.255.192
e. A connected route for subnet 10.1.1.0 255.255.255.0
LLM Explanation: With an IP address of 10.1.1.100/26, the subnet is 10.1.1.64/26 (255.255.255.192 subnet mask). This will create a connected route for the 10.1.1.64/26 subnet and a local route (also known as a host route) for the specific IP 10.1.1.100/32. The other options are incorrect because they either specify the wrong subnet (10.1.1.0/24) or use the wrong subnet mask for a local host route (/26 instead of /32).

Question Text: You are responsible to configure a static route for the network 156.187.45.0/24 using the IP address 156.187.80.45 as the next-hop IP. Which command will you type to meet the requirement?

This command specifies the destination network (156.187.45.0), the subnet mask (255.255.255.0 corresponding to /24), and the next-hop IP address (156.187.80.45).

Question Text:

type the wildcard masks to match the requirement.
Requirement: Match addresses that begin with 110.20
Command: network 110.20.0.0 {wildcard mask}
Which of the following wildcard mask will you use to meet the
requirement?
LLM Explanation: To match addresses that begin with 110.20, the wildcard mask should allow any value in the third and fourth octets. Question Text: Which of the following network commands following the command router ospf 1, tells the router to start using OSPF on interfaces whose IP addresses are 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1?
LLM Explanation: The correct answer is d. The 'network' command under OSPF configuration mode is used to enable OSPF on interfaces that fall within the specified network range. The command format is: network <network-address> <wildcard-mask> area <area-id>. The wildcard mask 0.255.255.255 matches any IP in the 20.x.x.x range, which includes the given IP addresses 20.1.20.1, 20.1.30.1, and 20.1.40.1. The other options have incorrect wildcard masks that do not match the specified IP addresses.

Question Text: Which of the following is a correct form of CIDR notation?
LLM Explanation: CIDR notation is a compact representation of an IP address and its associated network mask. The correct format is an IP address, followed by a forward slash, and then the number of network bits. In this case, 192.168.1.0/24 correctly denotes the IP address 192.168.1.0 with a 24-bit network mask, which is equivalent to the subnet mask 255.255.255.0.
URLs: ['CCNA 200-301 Official Cert Guide, Volume 1 by Wendell Odom', 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classless_Inter-Domain_Routing#CIDR_notation']

Question Text: Consider the following scenario: Your IP address is 192.168.8.34, and your subnet mask is 255.255.0.0. What part of the subnet mask represents the subnet ID?
Choices:
a. 255.255.0.1
b. The last two octets of the subnet mask, 0.0
c. The first two octets of the subnet mask, 255.255
d. 192.168.0.254
LLM Explanation: The subnet mask 255.255.0.0 has the first two octets set to 255, which represents the network portion of the IP address. The remaining two octets (0.0) represent the host portion. Therefore, the subnet ID is represented by the first two octets of the subnet mask, which is 255.255.
URLs: ['CompTIA Network+ Certification Study Guide, Seventh Edition (Exam N10-007) by Todd Lammle, Chapter 4: Understanding IP Addressing', 'Networking Basics: IP Addressing and Subnetting, Cisco Networking Academy, https://www.cisco.com/c/en/us/support/docs/ip/routing-information-protocol-rip/13788-3.html']

Question Text: Which of the following are non-routable IP addresses? (Select all that apply)
LLM Explanation: The IP address ranges 172.16.0.0/12, 10.0.0.0/8, and 192.168.0.0/16 are all considered non-routable or private IP addresses according to RFC 1918. These address ranges are reserved for use within private networks and cannot be routed on the public Internet. The address 9.0.0.0 is a public IP address that can be routed on the Internet.
URLs: ['RFC 1918 - Address Allocation for Private Internets (https://tools.ietf.org/html/rfc1918)', 'IANA IPv4 Address Space Registry (https://www.iana.org/assignments/ipv4-address-space/ipv4-address-space.xhtml)']
